The Kubernetes Scheduler is a core component of the Kubernetes control plane. After a user or a controller creates a Pod, the Kubernetes Scheduler will assign the Pod to a Node. Then, the Kubelet, on that node, will execute the Pod.

ğŸ”¶ At a high level, the Kubernetes scheduler does the following:
âœ… At the beginning, every pod that needs scheduling gets added to a queue.
âœ… When new pods are created, they are also added to the queue.
âœ… The scheduler continuously takes pods off that queue and schedules them.

â„ There are 3 steps involved in scheduling a pod to a node by Kubernetes Scheduler:

1ï¸âƒ£ FILTERING
ğŸ‘‰ In this step, the scheduler finds the set of Nodes where it's feasible to schedule the Pod. 
ğŸ‘‰ In a cluster, Nodes that meet the scheduling requirements for a Pod are called feasible nodes. If none of the nodes are suitable, the pod remains unscheduled until the scheduler is able to place it.
ğŸ‘‰ For example, the PodFitsResources filter checks whether a candidate Node has enough available resource to meet a Pod's specific resource requests.

2ï¸âƒ£SCORING
ğŸ‘‰In this step, the scheduler ranks the feasible nodes to choose the most suitable node for Pod placement.
ğŸ‘‰The scheduler assigns a score to each Node that survived filtering based on active scoring rules.

3ï¸âƒ£ BINDING
ğŸ‘‰The kube-scheduler assigns the Pod to the Node with the highest ranking.
ğŸ‘‰If there is more than one node with equal scores, kube-scheduler selects one of these at random.
ğŸ‘‰The scheduler then notifies the API server about this decision in a process called binding.
